summary: The creator discusses how to travel to Europe on a budget, suggesting that saving $80 per week can lead to a European vacation. They explain the importance of traveling during the off-season, specifically March-April or September-October, to avoid higher prices. The video demonstrates how to search for flights on Delta, highlighting the benefits of flexible dates and selecting flights with fewer layovers. It also shows how to find affordable hotels on Hotels.com by filtering for 3- and 4-star properties and a good guest rating. Finally, the creator covers transportation options in Paris, recommending the use of public transport passes like Navigo over Ubers for cost savings, and suggests budgeting for food and activities.

transcript: Some of you do not believe me that $80 a week will get you a European vacation. But that's not true because I've done it multiple times. So let me show you how I do it. Firstly, let's just crunch the big numbers. $80 a week for 52 weeks will get you $4,160 a year. Now the question I always get is, is that enough for a European vacation? People seem to think everybody's spending 10, 20, 30,000 dollars to go to Europe. But that's not true. I've gone to Europe multiple times and I've never spent more than $4,000. And I'm not staying at hostels, room sharing or flying a flight with 17 layovers. It's easier than you think if you know where to look. The first thing you need to know about booking a flight to Europe is that Europe is like Disney. If you want to go in the dead of summer or you want to go over Christmas, it's going to be expensive. We have saved thousands of dollars by traveling on the off season. But that doesn't mean that we're traveling in the dead of winter. We've found the best windows to travel are March through April or September through October. Those are months that are still beautiful and great weather for walking around cities. But you're not paying the hefty fees associated with going in June or July. Next you have to know how to find the best deals on flights and hotels. So let me show you how to do that using an example trip. Two people had to de Paris this April. The first thing you need to do is look at flights. I'm using Delta, and I'm just using Delta because it's what I fly all the time. I'm sure if you shop around, you can find maybe even better deals, but sometimes they come with weird layovers like Canadian Air usually does like two different layovers. And I don't mess with that. So let me show you what filters I put in. First, I just put some example dates a Thursday to Thursday. So it's a week long trip. And we're doing Columbus to Paris. Any of the airports doesn't really matter. The important part is we're selecting My Dates Are Flexible. Because when we're just planning, we don't know what dates we want to go yet. We'll base the specific dates of our vacation on what flights are the cheapest. You can see I put in Thursday April 16th through Thursday April 23rd. It's a week. But it's actually cheaper to depart a day earlier by about $200. And that's fine with me. So I'm going to select that. So the cheapest flight leaves from Columbus at 6:00 PM and has you arriving around lunchtime the next day in Paris at 12:15 PM. The price that you see is including taxes, but it is for Main Basic. So if you want to upgrade, you can. I think Main Basic is fine. It's totally fine. I just love Delta's loyalty program, so I probably would upgrade, but that's just me. For flights, round trip, you're paying $1,046.26. That's pretty great for an international flight. Next, we're going to go to hotels.com on a private browser mode. But we're not going to book at hotels.com. We just need to get some info and then book directly on the hotel's website. So you type in my location and dates. We need seven nights in Paris. We want to be in Paris, not Paris and vicinity. And we don't want to be in the suburbs. So you can see the prices listed are for 3 or 4 stars. I typically don't stay at anything lower than a three star just because I like some of the amenities and I like a hotel to look a little nice and feel safe. But I'm fine with not staying at a five star hotel. So to me, four and three stars are the sweet spots. And the other thing that I select is a guest rating of very good or above. These are your reviews from hotels.com. People telling you whether it's a good place to stay or not. Once you get past like seven or six, it just starts to get a little seedy. And I just want to save myself time and weed out some places that wouldn't be a good fit for me. So the hotels listed here are around $118 to $121 nightly. You can see here. That means with our flight and our hotel, we now have a leftover total of $2,186.27. Next, let's talk transportation. The one time I really think you should splurge on an Uber is either coming from the airport to the hotel or back from the hotel to the airport. Ubers to and from airport, about $120. This is because you just got off the plane, you're tired, you've got all your luggage and you just don't want to mess with public transport. When you have all of your bags, it's just too much. You're tired, you just got off the plane. It's worth the splurge. So info from our flight and our hotel, and mapped out an Uber for about the time that we'd land. It looks like that's going to be about $40. But just to be safe, I would budget about $60 one way for each Uber trip, giving you about $120 to spend on those Ubers to and from the airport. summary: The video shows a person spearfishing in South Florida. The creator explains that it's important to hide behind rocks or coral when hunting to avoid being seen by the fish. They encounter a school of fish but are unable to spear them as they are protected. Later, they spot a hogfish and attempt to catch it, but it escapes. The creator notes that this hogfish is delicious and needs to be at least 16 inches long, but this one is too small.
on_screen_text: Location: South Florida, Catching My Food
key_video_elements: Creator, Food, Nature, Technology, Props, Text/Graphics
transcript: Catching my food. Whenever you're hunting, you want to make sure that you're hiding behind any rock or coral so that the fish that you want to eat doesn't see you. I locked onto a large parrot fish and while these guys do look big and tasty, you're not allowed to spear them because they're protected here in Florida. As I was following it, I ran out of air so I decided to swim to the top. And from the top of the water, I saw a massive school of fish. Sometimes there's something tasty hiding in the school, so I went down to take a closer look. But when I didn't find anything, I waved them off and continued my search for what could be my breakfast. I stumbled across the most delicious fish in the sea, which is a lionfish, and when I took aim, I needed to make sure that I hit it good because these guys are destroying South Florida. That one fish wasn't going to be enough to feed me though, so I had to be extra stealthy. As I went across the bottom of the sea floor, looking for what else I can eat. I swam up to this hogfish that thought it was completely camouflage, and when it realized that I saw it, it turned its camouflage off and slowly started swimming away from me. Well, this fish is delicious. It has to be a minimum of 16 inches, and this guy is just a little too small.
